  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>Is ACT better than CBT?</strong></p>
  <p>Neither is universally better. Meta-analyses find them broadly equivalent in outcomes. ACT may suit people who feel stuck in CBT's thought-challenging process or who want a more values-focused, philosophical framework.</p>
  <p><strong>Does ACT work for chronic pain?</strong></p>
  <p>Yes — chronic pain is one of ACT's strongest evidence areas. Pain acceptance (not resignation, but willingness to have pain present while engaging in life) is associated with significantly better functioning than pain elimination strategies.</p>
  <p><strong>Can ACT help with trauma?</strong></p>
  <p>ACT can be helpful for trauma, particularly for building psychological flexibility and value-directed living. However, for PTSD specifically, trauma-focused CBT or EMDR are the most evidence-based first-line treatments.</p>
  <p><strong>How long does ACT take?</strong></p>
  <p>ACT can be short-term (8–16 sessions) for specific concerns or longer-term for complex presentations. Like CBT, it tends to be more time-limited than psychodynamic approaches.</p>
